Attorney General John Ashcroft's speeches promoting the Patriot Act did not violate anti-lobbying laws, according to Justice Department investigators.
The Act, passed after 9/11, expanded FBI powers but faced criticism for intrusiveness.
President Bush urged Congress to renew key provisions set to expire, emphasizing the Act's role in tracking terrorists.
However, a coalition of diverse groups seeks to amend certain intrusive sections.
The debate over the Act's renewal highlights the delicate balance between security and civil liberties.
The ACLU urges Congress to scrutinize and refine the law to protect privacy rights.
